The Denver International Airport to Snowmass journey involves several stages that each present different experiences and potential challenges.

The first hour covers Denver metro area traffic and the initial climb toward the mountains. This section usually goes smoothly unless you're traveling during rush hour periods or weather events affecting the Denver area.

Hours two and three involve the climb through Georgetown, over Loveland Pass (if weather requires avoiding Eisenhower Tunnel), and the descent toward Glenwood Springs. This section takes longer during winter because of chain requirements and reduced speeds in snow conditions.

